# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

llama.cpp's hardcoded chat-template system (`src/llama-chat.cpp`) supports several
Mistral format variants (v1, v3, v3-tekken, v7, v7-tekken). The `MISTRAL_V7` family
(including the Ministral 3 model) wraps system turns in `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` / `[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]`
tags. The classic **Mistral Instruct v0.3** format (e.g. `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3`)
does NOT use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`; it prepends any system message to the first user turn
inside `[INST]...[/INST]` and closes each assistant turn with `</s>`. This format
has no dedicated handler today and falls through to the `LLAMA_2` fallback, which
produces slightly incorrect output. This plan adds a proper named handler for it.

**Constraint**: Only add new code — do not modify any existing `if/else if` handler
branches in `llm_chat_apply_template`, and do not alter existing lines in the header.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Enum `llm_chat_template` — must receive the new value |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Registration map, auto-detection, apply-template switch |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — New enum value in `src/llama-chat.h`

Insert one new enum value immediately **before** `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` (line 61).
All existing values keep their names and relative order; only `UNKNOWN`'s implicit
integer shifts by 1 (harmless — the codebase uses enum names, not raw integers).

```cpp
// Add before LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN:
LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,
```

### Step 2 — Register by name in `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATES` map (`src/llama-chat.cpp`, ~line 38)

Add the entry right after the existing `mistral-v7-tekken` line so that all
Mistral entries stay together:

```cpp
{ "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },
```

This makes `llm_chat_template_from_str("mistral-instruct-v3")` work directly and
is the primary route for models that embed the name in their tokenizer config.

### Step 3 — Content-based auto-detection in `llm_chat_detect_template` (`src/llama-chat.cpp`, ~line 121)

The function's `[INST]` branch currently reads (abbreviated):

```cpp
} else if (tmpl.find("mistral") == 0 || tmpl_contains("[INST]")) {
    if (tmpl_contains("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]")) {
        return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7;           // Ministral 3 / v7
    } else if (tmpl_contains("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") || tmpl_contains("' [INST] ' + system_message")) {
        // ... v1 / v3 / v3-tekken dispatch ...
    } else {
        // llama2 variants — currently the fallback
        bool support_system_message = tmpl_contains("<<SYS>>");
        bool add_bos_inside_history = tmpl_contains("bos_token + '[INST]");
        bool strip_message          = tmpl_contains("content.strip()");
        if (strip_message) { return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2_SYS_STRIP; }
        else if (add_bos_inside_history) { return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2_SYS_BOS; }
        else if (support_system_message) { return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2_SYS; }
        else { return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2; }
    }
}
```

**Add** the following block at the very top of the `else {` body, before the
existing `bool support_system_message` line:

```cpp
// mistral-instruct-v3: plain [INST]/[/INST] format with no [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
// Absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT] distinguishes this from the Ministral 3 handler
// (LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V7) which is caught in the branch above.
if (!tmpl_contains("<<SYS>>") &&
    !tmpl_contains("bos_token + '[INST]") &&
    !tmpl_contains("content.strip()")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
}
```

Logic walkthrough:
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` present → caught earlier as `MISTRAL_V7` (Ministral 3) ✓
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` or v1 marker present → caught earlier as v1/v3/v3-tekken ✓
- Reaches `else` block → `[INST]` but no Ministral-3 / v1 / v3 / v3-tekken markers
- New check: if no llama2-specific markers (`<<SYS>>`, `bos_token + '[INST]'`,
  `content.strip()`) → **mistral-instruct-v3** ✓
- llama2 variant markers present → falls through to existing LLAMA_2_SYS / LLAMA_2_SYS_BOS /
  LLAMA_2_SYS_STRIP returns (still reachable) ✓
- The bare `return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_LLAMA_2` fallback becomes unreachable — this is
  intentional; the mistral-instruct-v3 handler produces the same wire format for
  that case and is semantically more accurate.

### Step 4 — Apply-template handler in `llm_chat_apply_template` (`src/llama-chat.cpp`, ~line 291)

Insert a **new** `else if` block immediately after the closing `}` of the
`MISTRAL_V1 || MISTRAL_V3 || MISTRAL_V3_TEKKEN` block (currently ends ~line 291)
and before the start of the `LLAMA_2` block:

```cpp
} else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format
    // - No [SYSTEM_PROMPT] tags (distinguishes from Ministral 3 / MISTRAL_V7)
    // - System message is prepended to the first user turn, separated by "\n\n"
    // - User turns: [INST] content [/INST]
    // - Assistant turns: content</s>
    std::string sys;
    bool first_user = true;
    for (auto message : chat) {
        std::string role(message->role);
        std::string content(message->content);
        if (role == "system") {
            sys = content;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            ss << "[INST] ";
            if (first_user && !sys.empty()) {
                ss << sys << "\n\n";
                first_user = false;
            }
            ss << content << " [/INST]";
        } else {
            ss << content << "</s>";
        }
    }
```

Format produced for a system + 2-turn conversation:
```
[INST] {sys}\n\n{user1} [/INST]{assistant1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]
```

No `add_ass` epilogue needed — consistent with MISTRAL_V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN which also
omit it (the model generates directly after `[/INST]`).

---

## Exact Edit Locations (line references from current file)

| # | File | After line | Action |
|---|------|-----------|--------|
| 1 | `src/llama-chat.h` | 60 (`LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_SOLAR_OPEN,`) | Insert `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,` |
| 2 | `src/llama-chat.cpp` | 38 (`"mistral-v7-tekken"` entry) | Insert map entry |
| 3 | `src/llama-chat.cpp` | 120 (start of the `else {` body in detect) | Insert early-return if-block |
| 4 | `src/llama-chat.cpp` | 291 (closing `}` of V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN handler) | Insert new `else if` handler block |

---

## Verification

1. **Name-based lookup**: Call `llm_chat_template_from_str("mistral-instruct-v3")` and
   verify it returns `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3`.

2. **Content-based detection**: Pass the actual Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template
   string (contains `[INST]`, no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, no `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`, no `<<SYS>>`)
   to `llm_chat_detect_template()` and verify it returns `MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3`.

3. **Existing detection unaffected**: Verify that `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`-bearing templates
   still resolve to `MISTRAL_V7`, and `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` templates still resolve to
   `MISTRAL_V3` / `MISTRAL_V3_TEKKEN`. Llama-2 `<<SYS>>`-bearing templates still
   resolve to `LLAMA_2_SYS` variants.

4. **Apply-template output** — exercising the new handler with:
   - System-only → prepended to first user turn
   - User + assistant + user (multi-turn) → verify `</s>` between turns, `[INST]...[/INST]` per user, system absent from 2nd turn
   - No system message → plain `[INST] content [/INST]` wrapping

5. **Build**: `cmake --build build` should produce no new warnings or errors.

6. **Existing tests**: `tests/test-chat-template` should still pass for all
   pre-existing templates (no handler modifications means no regressions).

