Here's the complete implementation plan:

---

## Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

### Context
The existing `MISTRAL_V7` handler (Ministral 3) uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`/`[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]` tags. The classic **Mistral Instruct v0.3** format has no such tags — system messages are prepended to the first user turn inside `[INST]...[/INST]`, and assistant turns close with `</s>`. Today this format falls through to the `LLAMA_2` fallback; this plan gives it a proper dedicated handler.

### Constraint recap
Only new code is added. Existing handler branches and existing header lines are untouched.

---

### 4 Surgical Edits (both files)

#### 1 · `src/llama-chat.h` — new enum value (after line 60)
```cpp
LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,   // before LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN
```

#### 2 · `src/llama-chat.cpp` — registration map (after the `mistral-v7-tekken` entry, ~line 38)
```cpp
{ "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },
```

#### 3 · `src/llama-chat.cpp` — auto-detection (`llm_chat_detect_template`, inside the `else {` block, before `bool support_system_message`, ~line 121)
```cpp
// mistral-instruct-v3: plain [INST]/[/INST] with no [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
// Absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT] distinguishes it from the Ministral 3 (MISTRAL_V7) handler above.
if (!tmpl_contains("<<SYS>>") &&
    !tmpl_contains("bos_token + '[INST]") &&
    !tmpl_contains("content.strip()")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
}
```
This fires only after `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (→ v7) and `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`/v1 markers (→ v1/v3/v3-tekken) have already been checked and missed. Llama-2 variants that have `<<SYS>>`, `bos_token + '[INST]'`, or `content.strip()` still fall through to their existing returns.

#### 4 · `src/llama-chat.cpp` — apply handler (new `else if` after the V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN block, ~line 291)
```cpp
} else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
    // No [SYSTEM_PROMPT] tags. System is prepended to the first user turn only.
    std::string sys;
    bool first_user = true;
    for (auto message : chat) {
        std::string role(message->role);
        std::string content(message->content);
        if (role == "system") {
            sys = content;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            ss << "[INST] ";
            if (first_user && !sys.empty()) {
                ss << sys << "\n\n";
                first_user = false;
            }
            ss << content << " [/INST]";
        } else {
            ss << content << "</s>";
        }
    }
```
Output: `[INST] {sys}\n\n{user1} [/INST]{assistant1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]…`  
No `add_ass` epilogue — consistent with V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN; the model generates right after `[/INST]`.

### Verification
- Name lookup: `llm_chat_template_from_str("mistral-instruct-v3")` returns the new enum.
- Content detection: A Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template (has `[INST]`, no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, no `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`, no `<<SYS>>`) → `MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3`.
- Regressions: `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` → still `MISTRAL_V7`; `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` → still v3/v3-tekken; `<<SYS>>` templates → still `LLAMA_2_SYS` variants.
- Build: `cmake --build build` clean.
- Existing `tests/test-chat-template` suite passes unchanged.

